The paper deals with market allocation and efficiency in networked markets, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The use of graphs and networks suggests a possible sub-category of networked systems (cs.NI). The analysis of demand functions and efficiency in markets involves computational methods and algorithms, which could fall under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The study of equilibrium and welfare maximization in markets involves social choice theory, which could fall under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the study of price competition and monopolies in markets involves economic theory, which could fall under the category of electronic commerce (cs.EC).
